# Git Branch Operations — Explicit Approval Required

## 🚫 Prohibited Without User Instruction
- Creating, switching, renaming, or deleting git branches
- Commands such as `git checkout -b ...`, `git switch ...`, `git checkout ...` without explicit user approval
- Any implicit branching workflow (e.g., auto-creating feature branches)

## ✅ Default Behavior
- Work strictly on the current branch snapshot unless the user instructs otherwise
- Use only git commands when interacting with the terminal; do not run non-git commands unless the user asks for them
- Safe operations on the current branch (when asked to save work):
  - `git add -A`
  - `git commit -m "type(scope): message"` (conventional commits)
  - `git push` (to the current branch only)

## 🧭 When Branching IS Requested by the User
1. Confirm the target branch name and base branch
2. Create and switch: `git checkout -b <new-branch> <base>`
3. Perform commits and `git push --set-upstream origin <new-branch>`
4. Do not switch branches again unless explicitly instructed

## 🛑 Accidental Branch Changes
- If a branch change occurs without instruction, do NOT attempt further branch operations autonomously
- Inform the user and await explicit guidance (whether to keep, rename, or switch back)

## 📝 Commit Message Standard
- Use English and conventional commits (e.g., `feat(web/playground): split layers`)

